00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:05.790
DAVE BURKE: Thanks, Hugo.

00:06:05.790 --> 00:06:08.850
Our brain's visual cortex is
especially sensitive to the

00:06:08.850 --> 00:06:10.020
physics of motion.

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:14.580
It notices delays of as little
as 10 milliseconds.

00:06:14.580 --> 00:06:17.530
So with Jelly Bean, we put a lot
of effort into making the

00:06:17.530 --> 00:06:21.090
user interface fast,
fluid, and smooth.

00:06:21.090 --> 00:06:23.960
This is the project that
we call Project Butter.

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:26.810
The first thing we did was
improve the system frame rate

00:06:26.810 --> 00:06:28.530
and make it consistent.

00:06:28.530 --> 00:06:31.670
We took the display refresh
signal, called vSync, and

00:06:31.670 --> 00:06:35.310
extended it to drive the entire
Android framework at 60

00:06:35.310 --> 00:06:36.420
frames per second.

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:39.750
That's one heartbeat about
every 16 milliseconds.

00:06:39.750 --> 00:06:42.400
And now everything runs in
lockstep, application

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:44.950
rendering, touchscreen
processing, screen

00:06:44.950 --> 00:06:47.560
composition, and display
refresh.

00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:50.360
In Jelly Bean, we also
introduced triple buffering in

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:51.290
the graphics pipeline.

00:06:51.290 --> 00:06:55.310
And this allows the GPU, the
CPU, and display to all run in

00:06:55.310 --> 00:06:58.230
parallel without waiting
on each other.

00:06:58.230 --> 00:07:00.250
The result is a more consistent
rendering

00:07:00.250 --> 00:07:02.900
framework, and everything
feels a lot smoother.

00:07:02.900 --> 00:07:07.550
Scrolling, paging, animations,
they're all buttery smooth.

00:07:07.550 --> 00:07:10.550
Next, we focused on improving
touch experience by solving

00:07:10.550 --> 00:07:12.080
two problems.

00:07:12.080 --> 00:07:15.000
The first problem is that touch
events are reported

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.140
independently of
screen update.

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:20.490
In Jelly Bean, we now actually
anticipate where your finger

00:07:20.490 --> 00:07:23.630
will be at the time of screen
refresh and use that position

00:07:23.630 --> 00:07:25.460
to draw the display.

00:07:25.460 --> 00:07:26.900
This results in a more
reactive and

00:07:26.900 --> 00:07:28.910
uniform touch response.

00:07:28.910 --> 00:07:32.050
The second problem relates to
how devices conserve power.

00:07:32.050 --> 00:07:35.330
They actually dial the CPU back
to a lower frequency when

00:07:35.330 --> 00:07:37.700
there's not much activity in
the system, and if you

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:40.700
interact with the system in that
state, it can potentially

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:43.090
take 10s of milliseconds
for the CPU

00:07:43.090 --> 00:07:44.360
to ramp up and respond.

00:07:44.360 --> 00:07:46.380
And this can lead to
a sluggish UI.

00:07:46.380 --> 00:07:48.970
So in Jelly Bean, we introduced
the concept of

00:07:48.970 --> 00:07:50.540
Touch Input Boost.

00:07:50.540 --> 00:07:53.090
Now when you interact with the
screen, we'll instantly ramp

00:07:53.090 --> 00:07:54.190
the CPU up.

00:07:54.190 --> 00:07:56.700
It's literally putting the full
power of the CPU at your

00:07:56.700 --> 00:07:58.360
fingertips.

00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:01.200
Now, one of our goals when we
started to work in Jelly Bean

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:03.660
was to be able to measure
and improve interactive

00:08:03.660 --> 00:08:05.790
performance in a
scientific way.

00:08:05.790 --> 00:08:08.860
So we created a new tool
called systrace.

00:08:08.860 --> 00:08:12.680
And systrace collects data
directly from the Linux kernel

00:08:12.680 --> 00:08:15.070
and uses that to produce an
overall picture of what the

00:08:15.070 --> 00:08:16.970
system is doing.

00:08:16.970 --> 00:08:19.530
The data's represented as a
group of vertically stacked

00:08:19.530 --> 00:08:20.880
time series graphs.

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:23.570
And in this particular
application example, you can

00:08:23.570 --> 00:08:25.580
see that there's a rendering
interruption that's much

00:08:25.580 --> 00:08:27.076
longer than 16 milliseconds.

00:08:27.076 --> 00:08:29.520
And this results in
dropped frames.

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:32.130
When you look at the data, it's
pretty easy to correlate

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:34.159
that with the database
interruption here.

00:08:34.159 --> 00:08:36.159
So you know what to fix.

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:38.400
Systrace comes with the
Jelly Bean SDK.

00:08:38.400 --> 00:08:41.289
And it's a really useful tool
for device manufacturers and

00:08:41.289 --> 00:08:43.809
for you guys to optimize
the performance of your

00:08:43.809 --> 00:08:45.120
