So when it really dawned on me
that we were onto something

01:43:44.680 --> 01:43:49.280
was when I started seeing people
in our team posting

01:43:49.280 --> 01:43:53.150
pictures on Google+ while
running with it.

01:43:56.950 --> 01:44:02.910
And if it's not super
comfortable and super sturdy,

01:44:02.910 --> 01:44:05.530
how would you be able to show
off your serve like this?

01:44:05.530 --> 01:44:07.090
This is Max on our team.

01:44:07.090 --> 01:44:08.455
He wanted to brag
a little bit.

01:44:11.580 --> 01:44:16.440
But sometimes you want to do
less conventional sports, like

01:44:16.440 --> 01:44:17.787
jumping into ball pits.

01:44:22.660 --> 01:44:32.100
So we want Glass to work for
many people and most

01:44:32.100 --> 01:44:34.160
situations.

01:44:34.160 --> 01:44:40.160
And realizing that, we needed
to create a scalable design.

01:44:40.160 --> 01:44:43.550
We decided to put all the
components off to one side,

01:44:43.550 --> 01:44:48.160
creating an asymmetrical design,
but that's balanced.

01:44:48.160 --> 01:44:51.090
And what this allows us to do
is to design different form

01:44:51.090 --> 01:44:53.170
factors for the frames.

01:44:53.170 --> 01:44:55.570
And this is something we're
experimenting a lot with.

01:44:55.570 --> 01:44:59.070
And here you can see Mike, Liza,
and Maddie wearing their

01:44:59.070 --> 01:45:02.450
favorite styles.

01:45:02.450 --> 01:45:06.650
BABAK PARVIZ: So we have this
incredibly powerful platform,

01:45:06.650 --> 01:45:10.430
lots of capability integrated
into a very small

01:45:10.430 --> 01:45:11.830
form factor, wearable.

01:45:11.830 --> 01:45:14.220
And you might be wondering, what
is the impetus for our

01:45:14.220 --> 01:45:17.560
team to embark on this journey
to build this system?

01:45:17.560 --> 01:45:19.800
And what are the uses that
we envision for this?

01:45:19.800 --> 01:45:21.730
What's the reason for people
actually to put

01:45:21.730 --> 01:45:23.510
this on their head?

01:45:23.510 --> 01:45:29.790
Broadly speaking, we have two
broad regions of aspiration.

01:45:29.790 --> 01:45:33.800
The first one has to do with
communicating through images.

01:45:33.800 --> 01:45:38.270
And the second one with very
rapid access to information.

01:45:38.270 --> 01:45:40.260
If you think about actually
how we connect to people

01:45:40.260 --> 01:45:42.100
today, we might have
a conversation

01:45:42.100 --> 01:45:42.920
or we may call them.

01:45:42.920 --> 01:45:46.840
So there's an audio way of
connecting to others.

01:45:46.840 --> 01:45:48.430
We may send them an SMS.

01:45:48.430 --> 01:45:49.450
We may send them an email.

01:45:49.450 --> 01:45:50.320
We may send them a letter.

01:45:50.320 --> 01:45:54.080
So we use letters of alphabet
or writing to convey our

01:45:54.080 --> 01:45:56.290
emotions to other people of
how we feel at that very

01:45:56.290 --> 01:45:58.640
moment or at any given
point in time.

01:45:58.640 --> 01:46:02.330
And we believe, actually,
communication with images and

01:46:02.330 --> 01:46:05.680
access to devices that empower
people to communicate with

01:46:05.680 --> 01:46:10.940
images in new ways are truly
revolutionary and may actually

01:46:10.940 --> 01:46:14.370
enable people to connect
in new and

01:46:14.370 --> 01:46:16.190
potentially better ways.

01:46:16.190 --> 01:46:20.660
Now, wearing a glass has certain
unique aspects to it.

01:46:20.660 --> 01:46:24.260
For example, when you have a
companion camera that's always

01:46:24.260 --> 01:46:27.000
with you, you can catch fleeting
moments in your life

01:46:27.000 --> 01:46:28.760
that otherwise would
be always lost.

01:46:28.760 --> 01:46:30.950
So this is an example
of a group member

01:46:30.950 --> 01:46:33.140
walking on the beach.

01:46:33.140 --> 01:46:34.690
I'm sure many of you
in the audience

01:46:34.690 --> 01:46:36.750
like myself are parents.

01:46:36.750 --> 01:46:40.720
And many, many times, you've
asked and wished that, oh, I

01:46:40.720 --> 01:46:43.240
wish I had a camera with me
right now to capture this

01:46:43.240 --> 01:46:44.960
unique moment with my family.

01:46:44.960 --> 01:46:49.230
When you have Glass, you can
actually capture those moments

01:46:49.230 --> 01:46:52.460
and have those memories forever
recorded for you.

01:46:52.460 --> 01:46:55.440
This is pretty important,
actually, when we

01:46:55.440 --> 01:46:58.250
enable such a thing.

01:46:58.250 --> 01:47:01.050
Another unique aspect of Glass
is that this is genuinely the

01:47:01.050 --> 01:47:05.550
first-person point of view
through your eyes

01:47:05.550 --> 01:47:06.500
as you see the world.

01:47:06.500 --> 01:47:10.060
This is one of our team members
finishing a race.

01:47:10.060 --> 01:47:14.160
And you can see actually how it
felt at that very moment,

01:47:14.160 --> 01:47:16.860
basically going through
a very long run.

01:47:16.860 --> 01:47:20.970
Or you might have a moment of
respite, and this is how the

01:47:20.970 --> 01:47:25.830
world looked to you as you were
enjoying a few seconds of

01:47:25.830 --> 01:47:30.400
break through your busy day.

01:47:30.400 --> 01:47:33.990
And going back to the theme of
family, you can actually

01:47:33.990 --> 01:47:37.820
record how your life looked
like with your loved ones

01:47:37.820 --> 01:47:41.270
through the first person
point of view.

01:47:41.270 --> 01:47:42.830
Quite important, I think,
and it could

01:47:42.830 --> 01:47:45.770
be very, very powerful.

01:47:45.770 --> 01:47:48.170
And honestly, there are some
moments that you may not want

01:47:48.170 --> 01:47:50.050
to record forever, but
sometimes it happens.

01:47:50.050 --> 01:47:51.440
So this is--

01:47:51.440 --> 01:47:52.500
oh, yeah.

01:47:52.500 --> 01:47:53.140
This is Will.

01:47:53.140 --> 01:47:54.010
He's sitting right here.

01:47:54.010 --> 01:47:56.170
He's one of our team members,
and he's just practicing pool.

01:47:56.170 --> 01:48:00.260
So these things can
also happen.

01:48:00.260 --> 01:48:03.100
ISABELLE OLSSON: So you've seen
all these unique moments

01:48:03.100 --> 01:48:06.560
that our team members have
captured just using the device

01:48:06.560 --> 01:48:08.710
for a couple of months.

01:48:08.710 --> 01:48:13.280
So all this footage is from our
team using Glass, which is

01:48:13.280 --> 01:48:15.580
pretty incredible.

01:48:15.580 --> 01:48:20.140
But what really excites me about
this is not only the

01:48:20.140 --> 01:48:23.590
unique perspective from your
point of view, but how easy

01:48:23.590 --> 01:48:26.450
and seamless it is to share.

01:48:26.450 --> 01:48:29.170
And I think this encouraged
people to do

01:48:29.170 --> 01:48:32.030
new things with it.

01:48:32.030 --> 01:48:34.740
We just saw how it is to
jump out of a plane.

01:48:34.740 --> 01:48:37.730
And you can experience these
moments where you feel like

01:48:37.730 --> 01:48:38.310
you're there.

01:48:38.310 --> 01:48:40.120
And you don't actually
even need a Glass

01:48:40.120 --> 01:48:42.660
device to do that.

01:48:42.660 --> 01:48:48.060
So here is, for example,
learning new things.

01:48:48.060 --> 01:48:53.030
This is Beau going through, step
by step, how to create

01:48:53.030 --> 01:48:56.390
very tasty dumplings.

01:48:56.390 --> 01:49:00.660
And I think there is something
really powerful about this.

01:49:03.920 --> 01:49:10.210
And sometimes it's all about
feeling like you're there.

01:49:10.210 --> 01:49:13.110
This stream of pictures
showed up.

01:49:13.110 --> 01:49:16.180
And I was sitting at my desk,
a little bit bored,

01:49:16.180 --> 01:49:17.190
and this comes up.

01:49:17.190 --> 01:49:21.150
And I had this visceral reaction
that I got so much

01:49:21.150 --> 01:49:22.180
anxiety all of a sudden.

01:49:22.180 --> 01:49:26.030
I could totally relate to
Stephen sitting in this chair.

01:49:26.030 --> 01:49:27.770
And these pictures continuously

01:49:27.770 --> 01:49:29.300
showed up in real time.

01:49:29.300 --> 01:49:33.260
And I was also able to write
little comments and say, dude,

01:49:33.260 --> 01:49:34.650
it's all going to be OK.

01:49:38.900 --> 01:49:44.270
And sometimes it's not
about grand things.

01:49:44.270 --> 01:49:49.740
Sometimes it's only about
communicating an emotion or in

01:49:49.740 --> 01:49:51.120
a situation.

01:49:51.120 --> 01:49:56.610
And this is Mike walking on
the street in New York and

01:49:56.610 --> 01:49:59.045
looking for some empathy from
his friends in California.

01:50:03.120 --> 01:50:04.960
BABAK PARVIZ: So the second main
aspiration that we have

01:50:04.960 --> 01:50:08.060
for Glass is to enable
people to access

01:50:08.060 --> 01:50:09.435
information very quickly.

01:50:12.610 --> 01:50:19.980
Nowadays, if you're looking for
answers to your questions,

01:50:19.980 --> 01:50:21.110
you may do a variety
of things.

01:50:21.110 --> 01:50:24.280
You may seek a friend and
ask them, what is the

01:50:24.280 --> 01:50:25.360
answer to my question?

01:50:25.360 --> 01:50:28.270
You may go to the library
and go through books.

01:50:28.270 --> 01:50:31.220
But more likely than not, you
will reach to your pocket,

01:50:31.220 --> 01:50:33.360
take out the cell phone, unlock
it, and do a search.

01:50:33.360 --> 01:50:35.700
And you get some amazing
results back, actually.

01:50:35.700 --> 01:50:39.250
We saw some incredible
technology just now

01:50:39.250 --> 01:50:41.030
demonstrated by Android.

01:50:41.030 --> 01:50:43.500
And what we aspire to
do is to make that

01:50:43.500 --> 01:50:45.190
even much, much faster.

01:50:45.190 --> 01:50:49.990
And some day, we would like to
make this so fast that you

01:50:49.990 --> 01:50:53.360
don't feel that you have a
question, you have to go seek

01:50:53.360 --> 01:50:55.820
the knowledge somewhere, bring
it back, and analyze it.

01:50:55.820 --> 01:50:58.920
We would like it to be so
fast that you feel you

01:50:58.920 --> 01:51:00.790
know it that fast.

01:51:00.790 --> 01:51:02.620
And that day may not be today.

01:51:02.620 --> 01:51:04.300
That day may not be tomorrow.

01:51:04.300 --> 01:51:06.330
But at least that's
our aspiration.

01:51:06.330 --> 01:51:09.570
And we would like to be able
to empower people to access

01:51:09.570 --> 01:51:12.490
information very,
very quickly.

01:51:12.490 --> 01:51:16.800
And in practice, basically, they
feel more knowledgeable

01:51:16.800 --> 01:51:18.910
about certain topics.

01:51:18.910 --> 01:51:22.810
Now, there are different types
of information that you might

01:51:22.810 --> 01:51:25.090
have in front of you.

01:51:25.090 --> 01:51:27.710
So for example, you could
be in a place.

01:51:27.710 --> 01:51:29.920
You would like to have
information about this place

01:51:29.920 --> 01:51:32.850
without disconnecting from your
physical environment.

01:51:32.850 --> 01:51:34.970
You might also want
to know how to

01:51:34.970 --> 01:51:37.200
navigate to the next place.

01:51:37.200 --> 01:51:39.260
There's a lot of interesting
information

01:51:39.260 --> 01:51:41.170
actually in this scene.

01:51:41.170 --> 01:51:43.050
Or you may be biking,
and you want to know

01:51:43.050 --> 01:51:43.980
how fast you're going.

01:51:43.980 --> 01:51:46.160
Obviously, you don't want to
disengage from the physical

01:51:46.160 --> 01:51:48.560
world, go to the computing
world, and come back.

01:51:48.560 --> 01:51:50.950
You want to remain engaged with
the physical world in a

01:51:50.950 --> 01:51:54.760
very unhindered way and still
get the information that you

01:51:54.760 --> 01:51:57.660
would like to have.

01:51:57.660 --> 01:52:00.280
Another thing that may come
up is that you may face an

01:52:00.280 --> 01:52:02.680
entirely new and unexpected
situation.

01:52:02.680 --> 01:52:05.300
This is a picture from a friend
of mine, [INAUDIBLE].

01:52:05.300 --> 01:52:08.200
He's a team member, and he was
sent to the market by his wife

01:52:08.200 --> 01:52:09.140
to do some shopping.

01:52:09.140 --> 01:52:12.720
And you just are baffled
at what you're seeing.

01:52:12.720 --> 01:52:15.050
And you would like to have
information right at that very

01:52:15.050 --> 01:52:17.465
moment in front of you without
disengaging from

01:52:17.465 --> 01:52:18.930
the physical world.

01:52:18.930 --> 01:52:21.320
So we are very excited about
this possibility.

01:52:21.320 --> 01:52:25.930
And I am particularly excited
to present this to you.

01:52:25.930 --> 01:52:28.680
Because the crowd here, the
people who are watching are

01:52:28.680 --> 01:52:31.540
some of the smartest developers
in the world.

01:52:31.540 --> 01:52:34.290
And I think you would actually,
hopefully, help us

01:52:34.290 --> 01:52:37.400
to figure out what kind of
information we should bring

01:52:37.400 --> 01:52:40.230
here and put in front
of people's eyes.

01:52:40.230 --> 01:52:44.930
The possibilities are
just incredible.

01:52:44.930 --> 01:52:48.000
ISABELLE OLSSON: So we shared
a little bit about our

01:52:48.000 --> 01:52:51.570
perceptive on Glass, and from
our team, and pictures, and

01:52:51.570 --> 01:52:57.030
videos, and also some of the
incredible things you can do.

01:52:57.030 --> 01:53:03.925
But what really sums it up
for me is this video.

